\begin_layout Subsection
Regularization Strength
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the BANFF ND constraint test statistic is defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\Delta\hat{\chi}_{\text{ND280}}^{2} & =\underset{\Delta\vec{y}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}}{\text{argmin}}\left\{ \Delta\chi_{\text{LLR}}^{2}\left(\vec{N}^{d},\vec{N}^{p}\right)+\Delta\chi_{\text{Penalty}}^{2}\left(\Delta\vec{y}\right)\right\} \end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{N}^{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{N}^{p}$
\end_inset

 are the binned data and prediction measurements, respectively, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 is the difference between postfit and prefit parameter values in the fit.
 This equation is similar to the general class of parameter regression using
 regularization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "springer_series978-0-387-84858-7"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{f\in\mathcal{F}}{\text{argmin}}\left\{ L\left(\eta,f\left(\vec{\beta}\right)\right)+\lambda J\left(f\right)\right\} ,\label{eq:GeneralRegularization}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a loss function of measurements 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $J\left(f\right)$
\end_inset

 is a penalty function, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\vec{\beta}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

-dimensional function of parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{d}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the regularization parameter, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a space of function on which 
\begin_inset Formula $J\left(f\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined.
 In regularized regression problems, the penalty term serves to solve an
 ill posed problem by adding external information.
 Similarly, the regularization parameter controls the importance of the
 penalty.
 We recognize that the loss function 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is the log-likelihood ratio term 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\chi_{\text{LLR}}^{2}$
\end_inset

, and penalty term is 
\begin_inset Formula $J=\Delta\chi_{\text{Penalty}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 with regularization strength 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In defining the BANFF test statistic in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:BANFF-Likelihood"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the regularization term 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 was set to 1 without justification.
 We can test the effectiveness of this choice using cross validation.
 Cross validation provides an estimate on the prediction error as well as
 determines the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

optimal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 choice of regularization.
 In cross validation, the input data is randomly split into 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 equal sized partitions.
 For the 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in K$
\end_inset

 data partition, we fit the model to the other 
\begin_inset Formula $K-1$
\end_inset

 parts of the data and calculate a prediction error 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this verification of the regularization strength, the test statistic
 is altered to include a regularization term
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\Delta\hat{\chi}_{\text{ND280}}^{2} & =\underset{\Delta\vec{y}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}}{\text{argmin}}\left\{ \Delta\chi_{\text{LLR}}^{2}+\lambda\times\Delta\chi_{\text{Penalty}}^{2}\left(\Delta\vec{y}\right)\right\} \\
 & =\underset{\Delta\vec{y}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}}{\text{argmin}}\left\{ \Delta\chi_{\text{LLR}}^{2}+\lambda\left(\Delta\vec{y}\right)^{T}\cdot V^{-1}\cdot\left(\Delta\vec{y}\right)\right\} ,
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:RegularizedDeltaChi2ND280}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the data is split into 
\begin_inset Formula $K=5$
\end_inset

 partitions.
 The prediction error 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 in this analysis is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{k}\left(\left(\Delta\chi^{2}\right)_{\text{trained}}^{-k},\left(\Delta\chi^{2}\right)_{\text{tested}}^{k}\right)=\left|\left(\Delta\chi^{2}\right)_{\text{trained}}^{-k}-\left(\Delta\chi^{2}\right)_{\text{tested}}^{k}\right|
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Delta\chi^{2}\right)_{\text{trained}}^{-k}$
\end_inset

 is the fitted model statistic on all but the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th partition, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Delta\chi^{2}\right)_{\text{tested}}^{k}$
\end_inset

 is prediction from the fitted model on the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th partition.
 This definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is useful since the penalty terms cancel leaving only the difference in
 log-likelihood terms.
 The optimal regularization strength is determined by minimizing the cross
 validation error,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{CV}=\frac{1}{5}\sum_{k=1}^{5}P_{k}\left(\left(\Delta\chi^{2}\right)_{\text{trained}}^{-k},\left(\Delta\chi^{2}\right)_{\text{tested}}^{k}\right)\label{eq:CVerror}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Alternative Penalties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider solving the linear regression with constraints problem 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{\eta}=X\vec{\beta}\label{eq:LinearProblem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $p\times d$
\end_inset

 matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 model features from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 measurements, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of regression weights with 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 rows, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\eta}$
\end_inset

 is a response vector.
 There are many approaches to solving 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LinearProblem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:GeneralRegularization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 A popular form is 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{2}$
\end_inset

 regularization
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "springer_series978-0-387-84858-7"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\vec{\beta}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}}{\text{argmin}}\left\{ L\left(\vec{\eta},\vec{\beta}\right)+\lambda\sum_{i}\left|\beta_{i}\right|^{2}\right\} \label{eq:RidgeRegressionGeneral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where an appropriate choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L\left(\vec{\eta},\vec{\beta}\right)=\sum_{j}\left|\vec{\eta}-X\vec{\beta}\right|^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

In 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{2}$
\end_inset

 regularization, the sum of weights squared is the constraint with strength
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With some algebra, we can rewrite the test statistic 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:minBANFFDeltaChiSqr"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 into the form of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeRegressionGeneral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Again, we recognize 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\chi_{\text{LLR}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the loss function 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 Now to tackle the penalty term.
 The (inverse) covariance matrix is symmetric and real and can be decomposed
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V^{-1}=U\Lambda U^{T}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 are the matrix of the eigenvectors and eigenvalues, respectively, of 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the eigenvalues are real and positive, the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as the square of a diagonal matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Lambda=\Gamma^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

We can now rewrite the penalty term as inner product of two vectors.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\Delta\chi_{\text{Penalty}}^{2} & =\left(\Delta\vec{y}\right)^{T}\cdot V^{-1}\cdot\left(\Delta\vec{y}\right)\\
 & \left(\Delta\vec{y}\right)^{T}\cdot U\Gamma^{2}U^{T}\cdot\left(\Delta\vec{y}\right)\\
 & =\left[\Gamma U^{T}\cdot\Delta\vec{y}\right]^{T}\cdot\left[\Gamma U^{T}\cdot\Delta\vec{y}\right],
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

and if we let 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}=\Gamma U^{T}\cdot\Delta\vec{y}$
\end_inset

, then the penalty term becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\Delta\chi_{\text{Penalty}}^{2} & =\vec{\beta}^{T}\cdot\vec{\beta}\\
 & =\sum_{j}\left|\beta_{j}\right|^{2},
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

and test statistic is now
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\Delta\hat{\chi}_{\text{ND280}}^{2} & =\underset{\vec{\beta}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}}{\text{argmin}}\left\{ \Delta\chi_{\text{LLR}}^{2}\left(N^{d},N^{p}\right)+\sum_{j}\left|\beta_{j}\right|^{2}\right\} \end{aligned}
.\label{eq:DeltaChiSqND280RidgeRegressionForm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We see that the BANFF ND constraint is a 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{2}$
\end_inset

 regularized regression problem with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}\propto\Delta\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 encoding the parameter weights and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

 by default.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can potentially improve the ND constraint analysis by utilizing different
 regularization terms.
 Another solution to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LinearProblem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 that is gaining popularity is 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

 regularization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\vec{\beta}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}}{\text{argmin}}\left\{ L\left(\vec{\eta},\vec{\beta}\right)+\lambda\sum_{i}\left|\beta_{i}\right|\right\} \label{eq:LassoRegressionGeneral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the constraint is the sum of absolute values of the weights.
 What is unique about 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

 regularization is that parameters that have no impact on the model prediction
 are 
\shape italic
exactly
\shape default
 zero.
 This is highly dependent on the regularization strength too, however.
 Further details can be found in the following reference 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "alma991031702535903361"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

